NAME: LUNA 2
GENERAL: Launch on 12 September 1959 / 22h 02mn (UT) from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe without instruments 1.2 m diameter and 390.2 kg. Sodium cloud released in space to help spotting. Confirms magnetic field and radiations belts lack around the Moon.
WALLS: Impact at 3.3 km/s with a 60° angle at 21h 02mn 24s in Palus putredinis. First human object to reach another celestial body than Earth. Two capsules 9 and 15 cm wide broken in the impact in pentagons with "USSR September 1959" written on them.
FLOOR: 30 minutes later, third stage of launch rocket impacts the Moon with unknown coordinates.

NAME: RANGER 4
GENERAL: Launch on 23 April 1962 / 20h 50mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Probe 3.6 m High and 306 kg. 6 cameras whom 4 high resolution ones. 2 solar panels 5.2 m span. 140 kg retrorocket for expected soft landing of a balsawood 65 cm diameter capsule.
WALLS: Bad functionning of on board computer. No picture transmission. Impact on Farside on April 26, 1962 at 12h 49mn 53s with a 9600 km/h speed.

NAME: RANGER 6
GENERAL: Launch on 30 January 1964 / 15h 49mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Probe 3.6 m High and 306 kg. 6 cameras whom 4 high resolution ones. 2 solar panels 4.6 m span.
WALLS: Impact on the February 2, 32 km away from planned site. TV camera failure before the impact.

NAME: RANGER 7
GENERAL: Launch on 28 July 1964 / 16h 50 mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Probe 3.6 m high and 306 kg. 2 wide angle cameras (25 °) and 4 high definition ones (From 8.4 to 2.1 °). 2 solar panels 4.6 m span providing 200W. Optical terrestrial sensor and wide gain transmission antenna. 2 internal energy network for best reliability. Recoed on magnetic tape and film after on board screen photography.
WALLS: 68 h hours flight. Hyperbolical orbit with a 26.8 ° angle. 4308 pictures transmitted from 13h 08 mn to 13h 25mn on 31 July. Last picture at 519 m altitude with a 50 cm resolution. Impact 16 km away from planned site at 2.62 km/s.

NAME: RANGER 8
GENERAL: Launch on 17 February 1965 / 17h 05mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Probe 3.6 m high and 306 kg. 2 wide angle cameras (25 °) and 4 high definition ones (From 8.4 to 2.1 °). 2 solar panels 4.6 m span providing 200W. Optical terrestrial sensor and wide gain transmission antenna. 2 internal energy network for best reliability. Recoed on magnetic tape and film after on board screen photography.
WALLS: Energy lost during flight then return to nominal. 7137 pictures whom 540 high resolution ones transmitted from 9h 34mn (2510 km altitude) to 9h 57mn. Last picture with a 1.5 m resolution. Impact with a 42 ° angle permitting panoramic views on the 20 february with a 2.68 km/h speed 70 km away from future Apollo 11 landing site.

NAME: RANGER 9
GENERAL: Launch on 21 March 1965 / 21h 37mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Probe 3.6 m high and 306 kg. 2 wide angle cameras (25 °) and 4 high definition ones (From 8.4 to 2.1 °). 2 solar panels 4.6 m span providing 200W. Optical terrestrial sensor and wide gain transmission antenna. 2 internal energy network for best reliability. Recoed on magnetic tape and film after on board screen photography.
WALLS: 5814 pictures taken from 13h 49mn (2363 km altitude) to 14h 08mn on 24 March. Last picture with a 30 cm resolution. Impact 4.9 km away from planned site with a 2.67 km/s speed.

NAME: LUNA 5
GENERAL: Launch on 9 May 1965 / 7h 55mn (UT) from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe 1474 kg. Same class as future Luna 9. Lunar surface probe 84 kg contained in a balloon. High speed impact on May 9 1965 because of retrocket failure.

NAME: LUNA 7
GENERAL: Launch on 3 October 1965 from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe 1474 kg. Same class as future Luna 9. Lunar surface probe 84 kg contained in a balloon. High speed impact on May 9 1965 because of retrocket failure.

NAME: LUNA 8
GENERAL: Launch on 3 December 1965 / 10h 48mn (UT) from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe 1552 kg. Same class as future Luna 9. Lunar surface probe 84 kg contained in a balloon. Could have soft landed on December 7 1965. Contact lost just before landing.

NAME: LUNA 9
GENERAL: Launch on 31 January 1966 / 11 h 45 from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe 1580 kg. Trip during 3.5 days. Retrorocket activated from 75 km altitude during 46s. Lunar surface probe contained in a balloon released few meters before impact. First lunar soft landing on February 3, 1966 at 18h 45mn (UT).
WALLS: Egg shaped surface probe 82 kg with instruments and cameras. Four solar panels opened after landing. Sealed container with internal heating and batteries. TV camera with orientable mirror. 3 pictures series with 27 total whom first lunar surface panorama.
FLOOR: Hard soil confirmation. Stereo pictures obtained because of movement soil. Radiations datas. Functionnal until 7 february when batteries failed.

NAME: SURVEYOR 1
GENERAL: Launch on 30 May 1966 / 14h 41mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Probe featuring 330 kg equipment and 537 kg propellants. 1 retrorocket used until 97 km altitude and 3 descent engines cut at 5 m altitude. 1 TV color camera. 3 legs 4.2 m wide. Mast 3 m high with solar panels and high gain antenna.
WALLS: Soft landing on June 2, 1966. 50 km away from planned site. 11237 pictures transmitted. Hard soil confirmation. Functionnal until october 1966. Reactivated during january 1967.

NAME: LUNAR ORBITER 1
GENERAL: Launch on 10 August 1966 / 19h 26mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Lunar orbiter which goal was to photography potential human landing sites. 1.65 m high. 1.5 m wide. Four solars panels 3.72 m span.
WALLS: Lower orbit altitude 40,5 km. 42 high resolution pictures and 187 medium resolution pictures taken from 18 August to 29 August and readout from 14 September. Impact on october 29, 1966 during 577 th orbit.
FLOOR: First pictures of the Earth taken from the Moon. Detection of pear shape of the Moon. No meteoritical impacts on the probe.

NAME: SURVEYOR 2
GENERAL: Launch on 20 September 1966 / 12h 32mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Probe featuring 330 kg equipment and 537 kg propellants. 1 retrorocket used until 97 km altitude and 3 descent engines cut at 5 m altitude. 1 TV color camera. 3 legs 4.2 m wide. Mast 3 m high with solar panels and high gain antenna.
WALLS: Descent engine failure. Impact on September 22, 1966.

NAME: LUNAR ORBITER 2
GENERAL: Launch on 6 November 1966 / 23h 21mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Lunar orbiter which goal was to photography potential human landing sites. 1.65 m high. 1.5 m wide. Four solars panels 3.72 m span.
WALLS: Lower orbit altitude 49,7 km. 609 high resolution pictures (until 1 m) and 208 medium resolution pictures taken from 18 August to 25 November and readout from 17 December. Impact on October 11, 1967.
FLOOR: Spectacular oblique picture of Copernicus crater.

NAME: LUNA 13
GENERAL: Launch on 21 December 1966  / 10h 19 mn (TU) from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe 1700 kg. Trip during 3.5 days. Retrorocket activated from 75 km altitude during 46s. Lunar surface probe contained in a balloon released few meters before impact. Soft landing on December 24, 1966 at 18h 01mn (UT).
WALLS: Egg shaped surface probe 150 kg with instruments and cameras. Four solar panels opened after landing. Sealed container with internal heating and batteries. TV camera with orientable mirror.
FLOOR: 3 panoramas. Physical measurements on soil with a penetrator, a dynamograph and a radiations sensitometer. Functionnal until 31 December.

NAME: LUNAR ORBITER 3
GENERAL: Launch on 5 February 1967 / 1h 17mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Lunar orbiter which goal was to photography potential human landing sites. 1.65 m high. 1.5 m wide. Four solars panels 3.72 m span.
WALLS: Lower orbit altitude 55 km. 477 high resolution pictures (until 1 m) and 149 medium resolution pictures taken from 15 to 23 February and readout from 4 Mars. Impact on October 9, 1967.
FLOOR: Surveyor 1 localization on the lunar surface. Film advance mechanism failure permitting only 25 % film readout.

NAME: SURVEYOR 3
GENERAL: Launch on 17 April 1967 / 7h 05mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Probe featuring 330 kg equipment and 537 kg propellants. 1 retrorocket used until 97 km altitude and 3 descent engines cut at 5 m altitude. 1 TV color camera. 3 legs 4.2 m wide. Mast 3 m high with solar panels and high gain antenna.
WALLS: Soft landing on XXXXXXXXXXX 1966. 6315 pictures transmitted Whom an Earth eclipse on April 24, 1967. Functionnal until May 1967. Visited by Apollo 12 mission astronauts on November 1969.

NAME: SURVEYOR 4
GENERAL: Launch on 14 July 1967 / 11h 53mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Probe featuring 330 kg equipment and 537 kg propellants. 1 retrorocket used until 97 km altitude and 3 descent engines cut at 5 m altitude. 1 TV color camera. 3 legs 4.2 m wide. Mast 3 m high with solar panels and high gain antenna.
WALLS: Retrorocket failure. High speed impact.

NAME: LUNAR ORBITER 5
GENERAL: Launch on 2 August 1967 from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Lunar orbiter which goal was to photography potential human landing sites. 1.65 m high. 1.5 m wide. Four solars panels 3.72 m span.
WALLS: Lower orbit altitude 99 km. 633 high resolution pictures (until 2 m) and 211 medium resolution pictures taken from 6 to 18 August and readout from 27 August. Impact on January 31, 1968.
FLOOR: Photographic coverage of lunar globe reaches 99 %.

NAME: SURVEYOR 5
GENERAL: Launch on 8 September 1967 7h 57mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Probe featuring 330 kg equipment and 537 kg propellants. 1 retrorocket used until 97 km altitude and 3 descent engines cut at 5 m altitude. 1 TV color camera. 3 legs 4.2 m wide. Mast 3 m high with solar panels and high gain antenna.
WALLS: Soft landing on XXXXXXXXXXX 1967. 18006 pictures transmitted. Soil composition realized with a 13 kg alpha particles analyzer on 100 cm2. Found basalt composition. Information on radar refectivity and temperature of soil. Functionnal until December 16, 1967.

NAME: SURVEYOR 6
GENERAL: Launch on 7 November 1967 / 7h 39mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Probe featuring 330 kg equipment and 537 kg propellants. 1 retrorocket used until 97 km altitude and 3 descent engines cut at 5 m altitude. 1 TV color camera. 3 legs 4.2 m wide. Mast 3 m high with solar panels and high gain antenna.
WALLS: Soft landing on XXXXXXXXXX 1967. New lift-off to 2.5 m high and 6.5 m distant landing. 30065 pictures. Soil composition realized with a 13 kg alpha particles analyzer. Functionnal until December 14, 1967.

NAME: SURVEYOR 7
GENERAL: Launch on 7 January 1968 / 6h 30mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Probe featuring 330 kg equipment and 537 kg propellants. 1 retrorocket used until 97 km altitude and 3 descent engines cut at 5 m altitude. 1 TV color camera. 3 legs 4.2 m wide. Mast 3 m high with solar panels and high gain antenna.
WALLS: Soft landing on XXXXXXXXXXX 1968 on crater Tycho slopes at 4500 m altitude. Soil composition realized with a 13 kg alpha particles analyzer. High aluminium percentage found different from Mare composition. 21274 pictures. Functionnal until February 20, 1968. Digs 7 tanches 40 cm deep.

NAME: LUNA 15
GENERAL: Launch on 13 July 1969 from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe 5700 kg. Same class as future Luna 16. Competes with Apollo 11 mission. Contains a lunar landing probe 1880 kg with return to Earth rocks samples capability. Lunar orbit achieved on 17 July. 52 lunar orbits completed before landing test.
WALLS: High speed impact caused by programming bugs in the gravity strength treatment module.

NAME: APOLLO 11 BASE
GENERAL: Launch on 16 July 1969 / 13h 32mn (TU) from Cape Kennedy. Vehicle 3,9m diameter. Command Module Columbia (CM) 3,65 m high and 5,6 t.  Service Module (SM) 7,6 m long and 23,2 t. Lunar Module Eagle (LM) 6 m high, 4,2 m large and 15,1 t whom 10,85 t propellants.
SLOPES: Neil A. ARMSTRONG (Commander) Edwin E. ALDRIN (LM pilot) Michael COLLINS (CSM pilot). First human landing on July 20, 1969 at 20h 17mn 40s. First surface walk on 21 July at 2h 56mn 15s. 2h 31mn walk. Distance 250 m at 100 m maximum from LM.
WALLS: 21.4 kg collected rocks whom 2 drillings. Early Apollo Surface Experiments Package (EASEP) with laser reflector, sismometer, solar wind measurement. Solar panels. End of transmissions of EASEP on August 27, 1969.
FLOOR: Lift-off on July 21 at 17h 54mn. Surface time : 21h 26mn. Splash down on July 24 at 16h 50 mn. Mission total duration : 8d 3h 18mn.

NAME: APOLLO 12 BASE
GENERAL: Launch on 14 November 1969 / 16h 22mn (TU) from Cape Kennedy. Vehicle 3,9m diameter. Command Module Yankee Clipper (CM) 3,65 m high and 5,6 t.  Service Module (SM) 7,6 m long and 23,1 t. Lunar  Module Intrepid (LM) 6 m high, 4,2 m wide and 15,1 t whom 10,75 t propellants.
SLOPES: Charles P. CONRAD (Commander) Alan L. BEAN (LM pilot) Richard F.GORDON (CSM Pilot). Landing on November, 1969 at 6h 54mn 35s. First walk on November 19 during 3h 56mn. Second walk on  November during 3h 50mn. Total distance 1350 m.
WALLS: 34.4 collected rocks. Recovery of 10 kg whom video camera on Surveyor 3 probe 180 m distant. Apollo Lunar Surface Experiment Package (ALSEP) with sismometer, ions detector, dust detector, magnetometer, spectrometer, atmosphere analyzer. Thermoelectric generator SNAP-27 using plutonium 238. End of Alsep transmissions on September 30, 1977.
FLOOR: Lift-off  November 20 at 14h 25mn. Surface time : 1d 7h 31mn. Splash down on November 24  at 20h 58 mn. Mission total duration : 10d 4h.

NAME: APOLLO 12 LM
GENERAL: Launch on 14 November 1969 / 16h 22mn (TU) from Cape Kennedy. Lunar  Module Intrepid (LM).
SLOPES: Apollo 12 mission Lunar Module (LM) sent to lunar soil to activate surface sismometers. Impact on November 20, 1969 at 22h 17mn 17s.
WALLS: Impact at 1.68 km/s with a 3.7° angle. Energy 3.36 x 10^16 ergs.

NAME: APOLLO 13 S IV B
NAMEDETAIL: Apollo 13 mission S IV B Saturn 5 rocket third stage
GENERAL: Launch on 13 April 1970 from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Third stage of Apollo 13 mission Saturn 5 rocket sent to lunar soil to activate surface sismometers. Impact on April 15, 1970 at  1h 9mn 41s.
WALLS: Impact at 2.58 km/s with a 76° angle. Energy 4.63 x 10^17 ergs.

NAME: LUNA 16
GENERAL: Launch on 12 September 1970 / 13h 25mn (UT) from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe 5700 kg. Surface module 1880 kg. Soft landing on September 17, 1970 at 5h 18mn. External arm. Digs soil until 35 cm deep. Surface time : 26h 25mn
WALLS: Return module Earth landing on September 24 in Kazakhstan with 101 g lunar rocks. Descent stage functional during sevral weeks sending temperature and radiations datas.

NAME: LUNA 17
GENERAL: Launch on 10 November 1970 / 14h 44mn (UT) from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe 5600 kg. Surface module 1814 kg with two ramps for Lunakhod 1 descent to soil. Radiocommanded vehicle from earth in real time.
WALLS: Soft landing in Mare Imbrium. Lunakhod 1 is 2.2 m long, 1.6m wide and 1.35 m high with 8 wheels, each with independant engine and brake. 756 kg mass. Solar panel electrical source. Internal heater with Polonium 210. Speed 1 to 2 km/h. Total distance 10 542 m during 10 monthes. Four cameras whom two stereoscopic.
FLOOR: Physical and mechanical lunar soil analysis with a soil tester at 500 different locations. Chemical analysis at 25 different locations. Magnetometer. Radiometer. Sends more than 20 000 pictures whom 210 panoramas. Mission ends on october 4, 1971.

NAME: APOLLO 14 BASE
GENERAL: Launch on 31 January 1971 / 21h 03mn (TU) from Cape Kennedy. Vehicle 3,9 m diameter. Command Module Kitty Hawk (CM) 3,65 m high and 5,7 t.  Service Module (SM) 7,6 m long and 23,5 t. Lunar  Module Antares (LM) 6 m high, 4,2 m wide and 15,3 t whom 11 t propellants.
SLOPES: Alan B. SHEPARD (Commander) Edgar D. MITCHELL (LM pilot) Stuart A. Roosa (CSM pilot). Landing on February 5, 1971 at 9h 18mn 11s. LM inclined to 8°. First walk on February 5 from 14h 42mn to 19h 30mn (4h 48mn). Second walk on February 6 from 8h 11mn to 12h 45mn (4h 34mn) until Cone crater. Total distance  3.45 km.
WALLS: 42.9 kg collected rocks. Shepard launched a golf ball with a sampler. Use of a special two wheels carrier. Apollo Lunar Surface Experiment Package (ALSEP) with radio transmitter, passive sismometer, active sismometer, ions and dust detectors, magnetometer and laser reflector. Nuclear thermoelectrical generator SNAP-27 with plutonium 238. ALSEP end of transmissions on September 30, 1977.
FLOOR: Lift-off  on February 6 on 18h 48mn. Surface time : 1d 9h 31mn. Splash down on February 24 on 21h 05 mn. Mission total duration : 9d 1h.

NAME: APOLLO 14 LM
GENERAL: Launch on 31 January 1971 / 21h 03mn (TU) from Cape Kennedy. Lunar  Module Antares (LM).
SLOPES: Apollo 14 mission Lunar Module (LM) sent to lunar soil to activate surface sismometers. Impact on February 7,1971 at 0h 45mn 25s.
WALLS: Impact at 1.68 km/s with a 3,6° angle. Energy  3.25 x 10^16 ergs.

NAME: APOLLO 14 S IV B
NAMEDETAIL: Apollo 14 mission S IV B Saturn 5 rocket third stage
GENERAL: Launch on 31 January 1971 from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Third stage of Apollo 14 mission Saturn 5 rocket sent to lunar soil to activate surface sismometers. Impact on February 4,1971 at  7h 40mn 25s.
WALLS: Impact at 2.54 km/s with a 69° angle. Energy 4.52 x 10^17 ergs.

NAME: APOLLO 15 BASE
GENERAL: Launch on 26 July 1971 from Cape Kennedy / 13h 34mn (TU). Vehicle 3,9m diameter. Command Module Endeavour (CM) 3,65 m high and 5,7 t.  Service Module (SM) 7,6 m long and 23,5 t. Lunar  Module Falcon (LM) from 6 m high, 4,2 m wide and 16,4 t whom 12 t propellants.
SLOPES: David R. SCOTT (Commander) James B. IRWIN (LM pilot) Alfred M. WORDEN (CSM pilot). Soft landing on July 30, 1971 on 22h 16mn 29s. First walk on july 31 from 13h 13mn to 19h 45mn (6h 32mn long). First excursion with LRV on August 1st from 11h 48mn to 19h 01mn (7h 13mn long). Second excursion with LRV on August 2nd from 8h 52mn to 13h 42mn (4h 50mn long) until Rima Hadley. Total distance 27.9 km until 5 km from LM.
WALLS: First use of Lunar Roving Vehicle (LRV). Four wheels with independant electrical engine. Stick driving. 76.8 kg collected rocks. Scott showed that a feather and a hammer falls with the same speed because of the atmosphere lack. Dig to 2.36 m deep. Rima Hadley survey. Apollo Lunar Surface Experiment Package (ALSEP) with radio transmitter, passive sismometer, atmosphere measurement, ions and dust detectors. Thermal flux measurement. Nuclear thermoelectrical generator SNAP-27 with plutonium 238. ALSEP end of transmissions on September 30, 1977.
FLOOR: Lift-off  August 2nd on 14h 25mn. Surface time : 2d 18h 55mn. Launch of a lunar sub-satellite on August 3rd on 20h 13mn. Worden 38 mn spacewalk on August 5. Splash down on August 7 at 20h 45 mn. Mission total duration : 12d 7h 11mn.

NAME: APOLLO 15 LM
GENERAL: Launch on 26 July 1971 from Cape Kennedy / 13h 34mn (TU). Lunar  Module Falcon (LM).
SLOPES: Apollo 15 mission Lunar Module (LM) sent to lunar soil to activate surface sismometers. Impact on August 3, 1971 at 3h 03mn 37s.
WALLS: Impact at 1.7 km/s with a 3,2° angle. Energy 3,4 x 10^16 ergs.

NAME: APOLLO 15 S IV B
NAMEDETAIL: Apollo 15 mission S IV B Saturn 5 rocket third stage
GENERAL: Launch on 26 July 1971 from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Third stage of Apollo 15 mission Saturn 5 rocket sent to lunar soil to activate surface sismometers. Impact on July 29, 1971 at  20h 58mn 43s.
WALLS: Impact at 2.58 km/s with a 62° angle. Energy 4.61 x 10^17 ergs.

NAME: LUNA 18
GENERAL: Launch on 2 September 1971 / 13h 40mn (UT) from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe 5700 kg. Same class as Luna 16. Surface module 1880 kg with samples return stage. Lunar orbit on September 7.
WALLS: 54 lunar orbits done before soft landing attempt. Interrupted communications just at soil contact on September 11.

NAME: LUNA 20
GENERAL: Launch on 14 February 1972 / 3h 27mn (UT) from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe 5700 kg. Same class as Luna 16. Surface module 1880 kg with samples return stage. Lunar orbit on February 18. Soft landing on September 17, 1970 at 5h 18mn. External arm. Digs soil until 35 cm deep. Surface time : 26h 25mn
WALLS: Panoramic pictures. Soft Return module Earth landing on February 25 with 30 g lunar rocks. Descent stage functional during sevral weeks sending temperature and radiations datas.

NAME: APOLLO 16 BASE
GENERAL: Launch on 16 April 1972 from Cape Kennedy / 17h 54 mn (TU). Vehicle 3,9m diameter. Command Module Casper (CM) 3,65 m high and 5,7 t.  Service Module (SM) 7,6 m long and 23,5 t. Lunar  Module Orion (LM) 6 m high, 4,2 m wide and 16,4 t whom 12 t propellants.
SLOPES: John W. YOUNG (Commander) Charles M. DUKE (LM pilot) Thomas K. MATTINGLY (CSM pilot). Soft landing on April 21, 1971 on 2h 23mn 35s. First walk on April 21 from 16h 47mn to 23h 58mn (6h 32mn long). First excursion with LRV on April 22 from 16h 33mn to 23h 56mn (7h 23mn long). Second excursion with LRV on April 23 from 15h 25mn to 21h 05mn (5h 40mn long) until North Ray crater. Total distance 27 km.
WALLS: Use of Lunar Roving Vehicle (LRV). Four wheels with independant electrical engine. Stick driving. 94.7 kg collected rocks. Dig to 3 m deep. Apollo Lunar Surface Experiment Package (ALSEP) with radio transmitter, passive sismometer, active sismometer, magnetometer. Thermal flux measurement. Laser reflector. Nuclear thermoelectrical generator SNAP-27 with plutonium 238. ALSEP end of transmissions on September 30, 1977.
FLOOR: Lift-off  April 24 on 21h 56mn. Surface time : 2d 32h 2mn. Launch of a lunar sub-satellite on April 24 on 21h 56mn. Mattingly 1h 24mn spacewalk on April 25. Splash down on April 27 on 19h 45 mn. Mission total duration : 11d 21h 51mn.

NAME: APOLLO 16 S IV B
NAMEDETAIL: Apollo 16 mission S IV B Saturn 5 rocket third stage
GENERAL: Launch on 16 April 1972 from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Third stage of Apollo 16 mission Saturn 5 rocket sent to lunar soil to activate surface sismometers. Impact on April 19, 1972 at  21h 02mn 04s.
WALLS: Impact at 2.5 km/s with a 79° angle. Energy 4.59 x 10^17 ergs.

NAME: APOLLO 17 BASE
GENERAL: Launch on 7 December 1972 from Cape Kennedy / 5h 33mn (TU). Vehicle 3,9m diameter. Command Module America (CM) 3,65 m high and 5,7 t.  Service Module (SM) 7,6 m long and 23,5 t. Lunar  Module Challenger (LM) 6 m high, 4,2 m wide and 16,4 t whom 12 t propellants.
SLOPES: Eugene A. CERNAN (Commander) Harrison H. SCHMIDT (Geologist and LM pilote) Ronald E. EVANS (CSM pilot).  Soft landing on December 11, 1971 on 19h 54mn 57s. First excursion with LRV on December 11 from 23h 54mn to 7h 07mn (7h 13mn long). Second excursion with LRV on December 12 from 23h 28mn to 7h 05mn (7h 37mn long). Third excursion with LRV on December 13 from 22h 26mn to 5h 41mn (7h 15mn long). Total distance in Taurus - Littrow valley 27 km.
WALLS: Use of Lunar Roving Vehicle (LRV). Four wheels with independant electrical engine. Stick driving. 110.5 kg collected rocks. Dig to 2.5 m deep. Apollo Lunar Surface Experiment Package (ALSEP) with radio transmitter, passive sismometer, active sismometer, gravimeter. Thermal flux measurement. Laser reflector. Nuclear thermoelectrical generator SNAP-27 with plutonium 238. ALSEP end of transmissions on September 30, 1977.
FLOOR: Lift-off  December 14 on 22h 54mn. Surface time : 3d 03h 01mn. Evans 1h 07mn spacewalk on December 14. Splash down on December 19 on 19h 24 mn. Mission total duration : 12d 13h 52mn.

NAME: APOLLO 17 S IV B
NAMEDETAIL: Apollo 17 mission S IV B Saturn 5 rocket third stage
GENERAL: Launch on 7 December 1972 from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: Third stage of Apollo 17 mission Saturn 5 rocket sent to lunar soil to activate surface sismometers. Impact on December 10,1972 at  20h 32mn 42s.
WALLS: Impact at 2.55 km/s with a 55° angle. Energy 4.71 x 10^17 ergs.

NAME: APOLLO 17 LM
GENERAL: Launch on 7 December 1972 from Cape Kennedy / 5h 33mn (TU). Lunar  Module Challenger (LM).
SLOPES: Apollo 17 mission Lunar Module (LM) sent to lunar soil to activate surface sismometers. Impact on December 15, 1972 at 6h 50mn 20s.
WALLS: Impact at 1,67 km/s with a 4,9° angle. Energy 3,15 x 10^16 ergs.

NAME: LUNA 21
GENERAL: Launch on 8 January 1973 / 6h 55mn (UT) from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe 4850 kg. Surface module 1814 kg with two ramps for Lunakhod 2 descent to soil. Radiocommanded vehicle from earth in real time.
WALLS: Soft landing in Le Monnier crater. Lunakhod 2 is 2.2 m long, 1.6m wide and 1.35 m high with 8 wheels, each with independant engine and brake. 840 kg mass. Solar panel electrical source. Internal heater with Polonium 210. Speed 1 to 2 km/h. Four cameras whom two stereoscopic.
FLOOR: Physical and mechanical lunar soil analysis with a soil tester at 1000 different locations. Chemical analysis at 25 different locations. Magnetometer. Radiometer. Total distance 37 km during 10.5 monthes. Sends more than 80 000 pictures whom 86 panoramas. Mission ends June 4, 1974.

NAME: LUNA 23
GENERAL: Launch on 28 October 1974 / 14h 30mn (UT) from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe 4800 kg. Surface module 1880 kg. External arm to dig soil. Planned for a sample return. Difficult soft landing in Mare Crisium. Damaged lander. Radio transmissions during 3 days. Lift off failure.

NAME: LUNA 24
GENERAL: Launch on 9 August 1976 / 15h 04mn (UT) from Baïkonour.
SLOPES: Probe 4800 kg. Surface module 1880 kg. Soft landing in Mare Crisium. External arm digging soil to 2 m deep. Sample return with 170 g lunar soil on August 22 in Western Siberia.

NAME: HITEN
GENERAL: Launch on 24 January 1990 / 11h 46mn (UT) from Kagoshima.
SLOPES: Cylindrical probe 1.4 m diameter and 0.8 m high. 197 kg whom 42 kg hydrazin. Includes a 12 kg small lunar satellite called Hagoromo with polyhedrical shape with 26 sides. Put on elliptical terrestriel orbit. Turns behind Moon on March 18, 1990 then 10 other times. Tests for first time aerobraking at 125 km altitude in terrestrial atmosphere on March 19. descends to 16.5 km lunar surface.
WALLS: Hagoromo put on lunar orbit on February 21, 1990 despite of its transmiter failure. Hiten put to lunar orbit Lagrange points. No captured particles found. Put on lunar orbit on February 15, 1993. Voluntary crash on lunar surface near crater Stevinus on April 10, 1993 on 18h 03mn 26s.

NAME: LUNAR PROSPECTOR
GENERAL: Launch on 7 January 1998 / 2h 28mn (UT) from Cape Kennedy.
SLOPES: 285 kg probe taking some ashes of Eugene Shoemaker astronomer in Apollo program. Put on lunar polar orbit on January 13, 1998 at 100 km altitude. Lowered to 10 km 6 monthes after. Total Moon mapping in various domains. On March 5, detection of water presence in darkened floor of polar craters.
WALLS: Sent on lunar soil on July 31 1999 on 9h 52mn near crater Scott. Impact observed by Hubble and Keck telescopes. No water emission recorded.

NAME: SMART - 1
NAMEDETAIL: Smart (Small Missions for Advanced Research and Technology)
GENERAL: Launch on september 27 2003 / 23h 14mn UT from Centre spatial de Kourou (French Guyana) by  Ariane V  rocket flight n°162
SLOPES: About 366kg probe. 1 M3 volume equiped with solar panels 14 m wide. Electrical ion drive. On board : a camera (AMIE), an X-ray telescope (D-CIXS), an IR spectrograph (SIR), etc... Put on lunar orbit on november 11 2004. Beginning of observations on november 2005. Orbit from 300 to 3000 km altitude
WALLS: Sent on lunar soil on september 1st 2006. Crash on septembre 3 2006 at 5h 42mn 22s in Lacus Excellentiae. Estimated speed 2km/s. Angle 2°. Impact observed  by more than 20 terrestrial telescopes as the CFHT, NASA-IRTF, SAAO, Tenerife and Calar Alto, and also 5 radiotelescopes.
FLOOR: Impact recorded by CFHT. Flash followed by a dust cloud covering 80 km2. Crater estimated to 10m x 3m and 1 to 2 m deep. Bright ejecta could reach 100 m in longitudinal direction.
